Heavy rain last night- calm at 11:00 AM.
Rained heavy in the morning of 8/10/86 - 8.67" of rain.
Your Department is reading Secchi disk on Big Cedar Lake along with other tests.
Very heavy rains- almost 6" in last several days- The Department of Natural Resources is doing other lake tests.
Rained again last night- took gauge out today- will reinstall May 1987.
Heavy rain the last two days.  Rained about 1" last night and drizzled past two days.
Sunny- south wind at 5-8 mph- and light rain last evening.
Sunny- warm- calm day with very little lake traffic.  No rain for five days.
Very windy- the boat is drifting fast.
Sunny- hazy- hot at over 90 degrees- and it rained hard for the past three days.
Quite windy- partly cloudy and lots of rain this past week.
Clear- sunny and warm- 9/25 had lots of rain end of September.
Tornado in Dodge County- last night lots of rain.
Too hot and too dry this spring!
Could it be that all the lakes are drying up
The temperature is 94 degrees today and nearly 100 tomorrow.
Good rain on Wednesday morning of 6/22.
Heavy rain on 7/16- small amount on 7/18.  Is everybody experiencing poor secchi disk readings this year
Why are the secchi disk readings going down
Getting more clear after rain last weekend.
Had plenty of rain on 8/22- 2+ inches.
This will be our last secchi disc reading for 1988 as our boat is out for the season.
Clear- warm at 86 degrees- calm- a beautiful day- heavy rain on Wednesday 6/13.
Very heavy traffic on Sunday 6/24- lots of rain last week.  When are we doing water studies
Very busy over July 4th.  I can't understand how the lake can be so clear with this much traffic.
I thought we were going to do some lake chemistry this summer
Quite windy again today.  Rain pretty hard over the weekend.
Have had more than average rainfall this month- but not so many 90+ degrees days.  Rain gauge not yet installed due to site remodeling.
A beautiful spring day!  Sunny- calm- clear- and a warm 86 degrees F.
Looks like an algae bloom is under way.  Had a lot of rain last night.
Sunny and northeast wind at 8-10 mph.
Overcast today and rain is likely.
Should reach 95 degrees today- sunny- slight haze- south wind at 8-10 mph- and very busy weekend on the lake!
Clear sky- sunny- and moderate boat traffic.
Rainfall in May was 0.7 inches.  Staff gauge on 5/27 was 8.17 and May 29 was 8.16.
The rainfall in June was 1.4 inches.  The staff gauge is 8.14 on June 4; 8.14 on June 7; 8.10 June 16; 8.05 on June 25; 8.04 on June 30.
The rainfall in July was 3.6 inches.  On July 12 the rain gauge was 8.28- on July 16 was 8.24.  There was 3.0 inches of rain in August.  The rain gauge on August 18 was 8.16.
The rain gauge on September 3 was 8.12- September 10 was 8.10- and September 15 was 8.18.
Lake a little cloudy for this early in the season.  Clear- warm and sunny today.
One inch of rain over the weekend of 5/22 and 5/23.
Very wind- cloudy- and lots of rain yesterday.
Lots of rain so far this year!
Seems to rain every other day.  Weed growth down- perhaps no sunlight.
The water temperature is 50 degrees F.
Cloudy.  Wind 20 mph NW.  Water temp 78.8 F.
Slight overcast and light wind from the southwest.  June rainfall to date is 4.5".  Last rain of 0.75" was on 6/18.
No rain the past week.  Bright sunshine- air temperature is 84 degrees- and wind 250 9.

Wind: 220 degrees at 14 MPH . Conditions: hazy- hot + humid. Last Participation: 17 June 1.5 hour steady rain. Thunder was present intermitantly. Temp: 84.2 F Barometer: 29.84. Assisted by: William Stoud + Robert Lawton

Winds calm- 1900 foot overcast skies- temperature 23C (73.4 F)  dewpoint 20 C (68F) very little precipitation since last monitoring date. Very slight alge bloom in progress. Assisted by the very capable Capt. Robert Lawton.
Cloud covere 10%.  Winds 5 mph.  Custer color strip reading: A2.  Site depth: 105 ft.  pH at 1 meter: 8.1.  Algae development: heavy (very green).

Skies clear- temperature 73.4 F dewpoint 55 F winds  110 @ 5 last percipitation was two days prior. Recent rains has temporarily eased the extreamly dry conditions.  Special thanks to William Stroud and Robert Lawton for their  assistance in taking the samples. It was very pleasurable being on the lake taking this sample. One more sample in October and another season has gone by.

Extramly wet spring June rainfall 12.26 inches. Skies were partly cloudy. Temperature was 87F and dewpoint 72F.  DO and tmperatures colleced were made with the district's newly aquired  HACH system. Assisted by Robert Lawton
Winds 070 dedress @ 4mph. Ceiling 3600 broken.Temp 22 C. Dewpoint 14 C. Barometer 30.09. Last rainfall 8/4. Total rainfall to date for August .79". Sampe collection assisted by Captn. Robert Lawton.

Wind were 180 @ 4mph. Ceiling: 6000 feet broken Temperature: 19 degree C.Pressure 30.25. The fall colors were beautiul. This was the first year using the HACH LDO meter. So much easier to use than the Van Dorn and Colormetric system. Special thanks to Robert Lawtonfor assisiting again this year.

Skies: Clear. Temperature:33 C. Winds: 290@7. Visability:  less than 10 mi.Dewpoint: 16 C. Barometric Press.: 29.87 inches. Warm + humid conditions last 4 days. Last Rainfall 5 days ago. Special thanks to Capt. Bob and Miss Sandy for their  assistance!!
Skies: Partly Sunny. Winds: 260@12 Temp: 22 C Dewpoint: 18 C Baro: 29.85 Last rain 4 hours ago .2ch Lst significant rain 4 days prior

winds: Calm Visability greater than 10 milws Skies: 100% clear  Temperature: 18 Degree C Dewpoint: `6 degree C Barometer: 30.13  Significant rain since last Friday in excess of 2.5 inches. Only .75 inch total rainfall in July. Would have liked to stay on the lake for the rest of the day. Special thanks to Capt. Robert Lawton for his much appreciated assistance. One more sample to go in Oct. and then we're done for another year.

Winds 010 dergees @  10-13 mph. skies: scattered clouds @ 300 feet agl.. Visability  greater than  10 miles.Temperature 6 C. Dewpoint -2 C. Looking at the temperature data the South Basin has already turned over. Killing frost occured in the first week of the month. Yet another year of collecting data has come to its conclusion. Thanks to Bobb Lawton for going out on the lake to assist this cold October day.

Winds were out of 160 degrees @ 6 mph. Visability 10 miles. Skies clear below 12-000 feet. Temperature 24 C Dewpoint 16C preasure 30.06. assisted again by Capt'n Robert Lawton. Encountered an early spring this year with warm weather just about the entire month of May. June has been pleasrnt but a little cooler than May.

Winds 160@6 MPH Skies clear. Temperature 22 C. Dewpoint 17 C Baramoter 30.01 On the evening of July 14 the area experienced over 5 inched of rain in a 10 hour period. Total July rainfall to date is alrady greater than the average July total. Special thanks to Bob Lawton for assisting me in taking the measurements

Wind 250  @ 6 Skies: overcast ceiling 400 feet. Temperature 6C Depoint: 14C Barometric pressure 30:07. Lastweek was very hot and humid but since Sunday tings have gotten pleasent again. Noticed a temperature inversion down to the thermocline. Skies were clearing bt the end of datat collection.Thanks to Cap't Bob Lawton for his assistance
Did two SWF tows    Collected 4 substrate samplers w/ John Stern

Winds: 220@3MPH. Visability  greater than  10 miles. Skies: Clear Temp: 11degree C Dewpoint: 8 degree C. Baro. Pressure 30.05.  We have experiencedourfirst frost of the season last week. Examination of the water temperature indicates that the lake has already "turned over". Water is extreamly clear. Special thanks to Robert Lawton for assisiting this morning.

Winds 220@12. Mixture of clouds and sun all day with off and on again showers all day. Temperature 22C Dew point 15C. Pressure 29.52 inches. It has been a cold wet spring. On this trip Paul Klien- Kristen kubisiak- and John Elke accompanied me for a storythat was published in the west Bend Daily News on 23 June

Winds 170 degrees @10 visaability 10 miles Skies clear  Temp 24 C Dewpoint 21 C Barometer 29.83. It has been warm this week with the temps since Sunday in the 90's. Dewpoints have been high as well. Thunderstorm rolled through around 04:00 this morning. Surface temperature of water is 83.12 degree F!!! Special thanks to Capt'nBob Lawton for assitingin today's monitoring effort. The reward for today's effortsd were three refreshing dips in the lake.

Temp: 19C Dewpoint: 13C Pressure: 30.09 Winds: Calm Visability; 10 miles. No rain past 9 days. Wonderful weather to be out on the lake taking measurements. Special thanks to Capt'n Bob and his dog Molly for thier assistance

Winds calm. Visability  more than  10 miles. Skies clear. Temp 13C. Dewpoint 11. Pressure30.22. Rainfall so far this month .01 inch. Special thanks to Robert Lawton for his aassistance in gathering this data.

winds 030@7 visability 10 miles Skies clear Temp 25C Dewpoint 11C  Pressure 30.18 We have had no rain since the second week in June. Last week over the 4th of July we had 3 consecutive days over 100F and the remINING DAYS WERE IN THE 90F's-Lake is probably 3 or 4 inches below normal. Special thanks to Bob Lawton for his assistance.

Winds were 120@6- Visability  more than  10 miles- Skies Clear-temp 20C Dewpoint 10C Barometric pressure 30.12 Lake level is down 6 to 8 inches from this summer's draught. Special thanls to Bob Lawton for his assistance in gathering readings. So far this summer August has been the best with rain once again returning and miltd temps.

skies clear- temperature 19C. dewpoint 7C winds 150 @ 5 mph visibility 10 mi pressure 30.16. It has been a unusually cool and wet spring- especially compare to 2012. It was a very pleasant day to be on the lake to collect this sample. Special thanks to Robert Lawton for his assistance and company while performing this task.

Winds 250@7 mph. Skies: Clear. Temp: 30C Dew point: 21C. Barometer:30 more than 29. Very little rain so far this month. Zero rain in the past 1.5 weeks. I was surprised to see such high DO levels down to 70 feet. Cool water temps and high DO indicate that the fishery will do well so far this summer. Once again Robert Lawton assisted with the sample gathering. At the conclusion of the sample an invigorating cool down swim occurred. A great day to be on the lake.

winds 060 @ 8- visability 10 miles- skies clear below 12-000 feet--temp 16C- Dewpoint 7C- pressure 30.23. Temperatures have been below normal for the past month (Lows at night 50 F Highs 75F) Not as many seagulls on the lake as previous years. Thanks to Bob Lawton for his assistance in gathering this data.
Measured site depth of 102 ft- Hydrolab hit bottom after 93 ft

Winds: Calm- Skies: Clear- Visability: 10 miles- Temperature: 15C- Dewpoint; 7c- Last rainfall 2 days pror about .5 inch. No killing Frost to date. Overall temperatures have been mild past month. Thanks to Bob Lawton for assiting in gathering data this past summer. Not much of a temperature difference at the thermocline or what is left of it- less than 8 degrees at depths between 30 and 40 feet.

winds 030 @ 6 mph  visability 7 miles skies overcast ceiling 700 feet Temperature 18c Dewpoint 15c Pressure 30.03 The secchi depth was the deepest I have ever encountered!! Another issue I have never seen before is that the water was green but there was  slight tint of blue as well. Lots of rain the past week and a half. On 18 June we had 3.7 inches- Humidity has bee high as well with cooler temperatures at night- Fog occurring nightly for the past week. Thanks to Bob Lawton for his assistance

winds 180 @ 8-  visability 10 miles- skies clear- temperature 23C- Dewpoint 18C baro 29.97. Measurements taken on a Monday after lots of boating activity over the weekend. secchi depth was 10 feet less than June's measurement. Slight alge bloom in progress Special thanks to Bob Lawton for assisting on this measurement

winds were 260@9 visability 10 miles- clouds 3000-bkn- 3600-bkn- 4000-bkn. depoint 16C. Temperature 24C. Baro 29.90. Beautiful afternoon to be on the lake. I would like to comment on my June Secchi depth reading of 26 feet. I have been doing lake monitoring for 13 years and that is the deepest reading I've ever recorded. Today's measurement was half of that reading. This will be my last report for 2014 and would like to thank Bob Lawton for his assistance tajing these readings. See yaou all next year.

Winds: Calm. Skies: Clear. Temperature: 18C. Dew Point: 11C. Pressure:30.05. Heavy thunderstorms 48 hours ago. Additional rain 36 hours ago. It was a picture perfect morning on the lake. Bright blue skies and lush green countryside. Sail boats were having a difficult time due to the lack of wind. Special thanks to Robert Lawton for his assistance and company on this data gathering!!!

Winds out of Northwest @12mph.Visabiliy 10 miles. ceilings overcast @ 2800 feet  Temp: 15C Dewpoint 11C Pressure 30.17. Cool temperatures last 3 days. Overcast skies last 3 days. This will be the last sample for 2015. Thanks to Bob Lawton for assisting again this year.
Winds 270 @15 gusting to 25. Visability 10 miles. Scattered clouds 3800 feet. Temp 29C Dewpoint 19C. Was assisted by Robert Lawton

Winds 080 @ 5 mph. Visability 10 miles. Skies clear below 12-000 feet. Temperature 22C. Dewpoint 17C. Last rain received 48 hours ago. (T-storm) Has been unusually dry month so far. Thanks to Robert Lwton for his assistance in gathering this data.
Winds 230 @ 3 mph. Visability 10 miles. Skies clear below 12-000 feet.  Temp 21C Dewpoint  13C. Very wet spring.

column1: .67 inch rain in last 48 hours. assited by Harold Eick. Somehow managed to loose an anchor taking the South basin measurements.

column2: Winds 060 @ 10 G 14 Visability 10 miles clouds scattered @ 3000 Temp 21 C Dewpoint 13 C Altimeter 30.03 The first time in over a week where the humidity has been tolerable. Thanks to Bob Lawton for his assistance.

winds 050 @ 5 mph- Visability: 10 Miles. Skies: Overcast  Barometer: 29.94 Temp: 19 C Dewpoint 17C  Few sprinkles during the measurements. Assisted by Robert Lawton with the sample. Rain showers occurred while taking sample. Thanks to Robert Lawton for assiting
winds 270 @7 Dewpoint 57F Baro 29.99 skies clear visabity 10 mi heplers Harold + Janice Eick

Winds were calm. visability 10 miles. skies were hazy due to smoke from wildfires burning in Canada. skies clear below 12-000 feet. Temp 22 C dewpoint 20 C. Barometer 29.97. Assisted by Bob Lawton. Only folks on the lake were us and a half dozen fishermen.
